My basic meme-stock corporate finance advice is that, if you are a public c=
ompany, and people want to pay a lot of money for your stock for no real re=
ason, you should sell it to them.
  [1]
=C2=A0If your stock is overpriced, you should sell it. This is good for you=
r existing shareholders, because you are selling shares for more than they =
are worth, which is accretive. It is bad for the people=C2=A0buying=C2=A0th=
e shares from you, because they are overpaying, but on the other hand=C2=A0=
they were going to buy=C2=A0the shares anyway from someone else on the stoc=
k exchange, so they=C2=A0might as well buy them from you instead.
While this feels right as basic high-level advice, there are some complicat=
ions that can make it tricky. The US Securities and Exchange Commission, fo=
r instance, doesn=E2=80=99t love meme-stock issuers taking advantage of dum=
b prices to sell stock, so if you=E2=80=99re going to do it   you have to w=
arn potential buyers that the price is dumb. (This is not much of an impedi=
ment; the buyers don=E2=80=99t care.) In egregious cases =E2=80=94=C2=A0if =
for instance you are=C2=A0actually in bankruptcy=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0the SE=
C   won=E2=80=99t let you do it at all.
AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. is a huge meme stock and has, over the last=
 couple of years, been particularly aggressive about selling stock into its=
 meme rally. In June 2020, AMC had about  104 million=C2=A0shares=C2=A0of s=
tock outstanding; now it has about  516 million. Roughly 80% of all AMC sha=
res were issued in the last two years, partly out of late-2020 desperation =
(a pandemic is bad for movie theaters) but partly out of early-2021 opportu=
nism (a meme-stock rally is great for movie theaters I guess?). Retail inve=
stor enthusiasm got AMC out of   some real financial difficulties.=C2=A0And=
 then it kept going. In March it  bought a gold mine? AMC, led by its meme-=
loving chief executive officer Adam Aron, has seized every opportunity prov=
ided by its legion of meme-stock retail investors to shore up its finances,=
 pivot into new businesses and become sort of a meme-stock conglomerate.
There is, however, a weird complication limiting how much AMC can do. A pub=
lic company=E2=80=99s certificate of incorporation will say how many shares=
 it can issue, and that number can=E2=80=99t be changed without a vote of t=
he majority of outstanding shares. AMC is limited to issuing  524,173,073 s=
hares of common stock. It has issued 516,820,595 of those shares, leaving a=
bout 7.4 million to spare, though some of those might be reserved for emplo=
yee stock-based compensation or other uses. In round numbers, AMC is out of=
 shares to issue. So it can=E2=80=99t sell more shares to raise money, and =
it can=E2=80=99t issue more shares to, for instance, attract new employees =
or buy new gold mines.
  [2]

AMC sensibly tried to address this problem by  asking shareholders to autho=
rize 500 million new shares, but shareholders objected
  [3]
=C2=A0and AMC ultimately=C2=A0withdrew the proposal. So it is stuck with th=
e shares it has. (I   once proposed that it should issue its last available=
 share for millions of dollars, because there is a ton of meme value to own=
ing the last AMC share, but I guess I was kidding?)
On the other hand, AMC has=C2=A0preferred=C2=A0shares. Its  certificate of =
incorporation authorizes it to issue up to 50 million shares of preferred s=
tock, and like most companies it hadn=E2=80=99t issued any.
  [4]
=C2=A0As is typical for public companies, this is what is called =E2=80=9Cb=
lank-check preferred=E2=80=9D: The board of directors can decide how much t=
o issue, what its rights are, how much to sell it for, etc., without shareh=
older approval. This is a pretty significant loophole. What the board can d=
o is issue preferred stock that=C2=A0looks like=C2=A0common stock. Specific=
ally:
=09The preferred stock can have the same voting rights as the common stock.=
=09The preferred stock can have the same economic rights as the common stoc=
k: If AMC pays a cash dividend on the common, the preferred gets the same d=
ividend; if AMC is acquired in a merger, the preferred gets paid the same p=
rice as the common, etc.=09The preferred stock can be=C2=A0convertible=C2=
=A0into the common stock, if AMC=E2=80=99s shareholders ever approve enough=
 shares.

Technically you have to deal with the 50-million-share cap=C2=A0on preferre=
d shares, but that can be managed: You can say =E2=80=9Ceach preferred shar=
e is equivalent to 100 shares of common stock,=E2=80=9D giving you 5 billio=
n share equivalents to play with. Then you can set up a depository receipt =
program where AMC issues shares of the preferred stock to a depository, and=
 the depository issues receipts for 1/100th of a preferred share to investo=
rs. Then each receipt should be economically equivalent to one common share=
.
This all sounds weird, when I write it down like that.=C2=A0But it is actua=
lly a pretty well-known technology, in the niche world of companies without=
 enough authorized shares.
  [5]
=C2=A0Surely lots of bankers and lawyers pitched it to AMC. Yesterday   AMC=
 did it:

AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s preferred stock made its debut Mo=
nday amid a selloff in other meme stocks and the broader market, making for=
 a volatile day. ...
AMC issued a dividend after Friday=E2=80=99s close of one preferred equity =
unit for each share of the common, in effect putting in place a 2-for-1 sto=
ck split. The preferred shares traded for the first time Monday on the New =
York Stock Exchange under the =E2=80=9CAPE=E2=80=9D symbol, a term Reddit u=
sers coined to refer to others who are bullish on so-called meme stocks. Th=
e split sparked some volatile trading, triggering multiple trading halts in=
 earlier trading Monday for both classes of shares.

Specifically, the trade was to (1)=C2=A0authorize=C2=A01 billion new APE un=
its, each of which is equivalent to one common share and (2)=C2=A0issue=C2=
=A0about 516.8 million of them to holders of existing AMC common shares as =
a dividend. So if you owned an AMC common share on Friday, on Monday you ow=
ned an AMC common share=C2=A0plus=C2=A0an APE unit. That is =E2=80=9Cin eff=
ect=E2=80=9D a 2-for-1 stock split: Each APE unit has the same economic and=
 voting rights as a common share, so you went from owning one common share =
to owning two-ish common-ish shares.
  [6]
=C2=A0
In practice, this is all a bit strange, and the APE units trade at a discou=
nt. AMC=E2=80=99s common stock closed at $10.46 yesterday; the APEs closed =
at $6.00. (AMC closed at $18.02 on Friday, before the split, so the total p=
ackage was down about 8.7%.) As of 11 a.m. today the APEs were up (to about=
 $6.53) and the AMCs were down (to about $9.91), and you might expect to se=
e a certain amount of convergence if AMC=E2=80=99s shareholders agree=C2=A0=
that the APEs are equivalent to the common stock.
  [7]

But the point isn=E2=80=99t really the stock split. The point is that now A=
MC has 483 million APE units that it hasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0issued. At yesterd=
ay=E2=80=99s APE closing price, that=E2=80=99s $2.9 billion worth of stock =
to play with.
  [8]
=C2=A0In its  Frequently Asked Questions about the APE dividend, AMC does s=
ome foreshadowing:

Authorized but unissued AMC Preferred Equity units can be issued in the fut=
ure in the same way that AMC can issue authorized but unissued shares of co=
mmon stock. Normal regulations and requirements with respect to share issua=
nces apply, including potential filings with the SEC and public disclosure,=
 along with the circumstances under which shareholder approval is or is not=
 required.
AMC Preferred Equity units provide AMC with a currency that can be used in =
the future to further strengthen our balance sheet, including by reducing o=
ur debt and other liabilities. The AMC Preferred Equity units also give AMC=
 the ability to invest in shareholder value-enhancing and transformative M&=
A investment opportunities. In addition, the flexibility provided by the Co=
mpany=E2=80=99s AMC Preferred Equity units immensely lessens any survival r=
isk as we continue to work our way through the impact of the COVID pandemic=
 towards recovery and transformation.

If you are a company with a meme stock, you should sell stock. If you run o=
ut of stock to sell, you should create more, and then sell it.
A few other points. First, the ordinary approach with this sort of thing wo=
uld be to try to convert the APEs into AMC common shares as soon as possibl=
e. AMC has in the past tried to get shareholder approval to issue new share=
s, but it has been rebuffed. Now, though, it has a fait accompli: It can go=
 to shareholders and say =E2=80=9Clook, these APEs are already trading, but=
 they are trading at a discount in annoying ways, so you might as well give=
 us permission to issue more common shares so we can go back to having a si=
ngle share class.=E2=80=9D Maybe that will work.
  [9]

But AMC doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0have=C2=A0to do that, and it has no immediate =
plans to. From the FAQ:

Technically yes, the AMC Preferred Equity units can convert into common sto=
ck, but only if the AMC Board proposes and then investors vote to approve a=
n increase in the number of authorized shares of common stock, in an amount=
 at least sufficient to permit the conversion of the AMC Preferred Equity u=
nits into common stock.
However, we do not currently expect the AMC Board to make such a proposal a=
ny time soon.
It is more likely than not that the two securities, the common stock and AM=
C Preferred Equity units will trade as two separate securities for quite so=
me time to come.

AMC is a meme stock, and APE is =E2=80=94=C2=A0potentially =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
 very meme-y security indeed. Why not see what happens? Maybe AMC can extra=
ct=C2=A0more=C2=A0value from APE by leaving it as its own separate class of=
 stock. The business of being a meme stock is largely about=C2=A0getting at=
tention, and having a weird APE unit might be more attention-getting than h=
aving one class of stock would.
Second, is there an AMC/APE arbitrage trade? You might take a view like: =
=E2=80=9CAPE shares have the same economic and voting rights as AMC common =
shares, and will eventually be convertible into common shares, but they tra=
de at a big discount. I should short AMC shares, buy the same number of APE=
 shares, and profit when the gap closes.=E2=80=9D Good luck to you with tha=
t one! I will not comment on it as a thesis except to say that AMC=E2=80=99=
s retail shareholders seem to be endlessly angry about short sellers, so if=
 you short AMC stock as part of an arbitrage trade they will probably be en=
dlessly angry at you.
  [10]

Third, speaking of being endlessly angry at short sellers: One tactic that =
we have talked about from time to time around here is that=C2=A0a company w=
ith a lot of short sellers can issue an inconvenient weird dividend to make=
 life difficult for the short sellers. The way short selling works is that,=
 to short stock, you have to borrow it, and when you return it you have to =
give your lender back whatever they would have gotten from holding the stoc=
k. So if a stock pays a $1 cash dividend, then short sellers need to pay $1=
 to their share lenders. If a stock does a 2-for-1 split, short sellers nee=
d to return twice as many shares as they borrowed to close out their shorts=
.
And if a stock pays a dividend of, say, seven magic beans per share, then t=
he short sellers need to go out and find seven magic beans to deliver to th=
eir share lenders.=C2=A0For instance, in 2019, Overstock.com Inc. tried to =
do a special dividend of preferred stock that traded only on its own blockc=
hain platform, and that was not tradeable at all for six months. A short se=
ller would need to go buy shares of that stock to deliver to her share lend=
ers, but she couldn=E2=80=99t, because it didn=E2=80=99t trade. =E2=80=9CAh=
a, got you,=E2=80=9D Overstock more or less cackled, and=C2=A0the shorts we=
re squeezed, though eventually this plan collapsed under the weight of   ge=
neral Overstock insanity.
This is not that at all! APE trades liquidly on the New York Stock Exchange=
, this is more or less a stock split, and it will be very easy for short se=
llers to deliver APE to their lenders. Instead of buying back a share of AM=
C, they=E2=80=99ll just have to buy back a share of AMC plus an APE unit. A=
n AMC share plus an APE unit this week cost less than an AMC share did last=
