=9D Hahn said that Twitter fired Zatko after 15 months =E2=80=9Cfor poor pe=
rformance and leadership.=E2=80=9D ...
A person familiar with Zatko=E2=80=99s tenure said the company investigated=
 Zatko=E2=80=99s security claims during his time there and concluded they w=
ere sensationalistic and without merit.

The Washington Post article quoted above includes a copy of Zatko=E2=80=99s=
 redacted complaint. =E2=80=9CPlease note,=E2=80=9D says a footnote, =E2=80=
=9Cthat Mudge began preparing these disclosures in early March 2022, well b=
efore Mr. Musk expressed any interest in acquiring Twitter, and has not com=
municated these disclosures to anyone with a financial interest in Twitter.=
=E2=80=9D
And, to be clear, Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0agree with=
 Musk=E2=80=99s. The   narrow issue in the Musk/Twitter dispute=C2=A0is whe=
ther Twitter has been=C2=A0lying in its securities filings when it says tha=
t it estimates that fewer than 5% of its =E2=80=9Cmonetizable daily active =
users=E2=80=9D are spam or bot accounts. And Zatko is pretty unambiguous th=
at, no, Twitter=E2=80=99s numbers are correct. His lawyers write:

Executives are incentivized to avoid counting spam bots as mDAU, because mD=
AU is reported to advertisers, and advertisers use it to calculate the effe=
ctiveness of ads. If mDAU includes spam bots that do not click through ads =
to buy products, then advertisers conclude the ads are less effective, and =
might shift their ad spending away from Twitter to other platforms with hig=
her perceived effectiveness.
However, there are many millions of active accounts that are=C2=A0not=C2=A0=
considered =E2=80=9CmDAU,=E2=80=9D either because they are spam bots, or be=
cause Twitter does not believe it can monetize them. These millions of non-=
mDAU accounts are part of the median user=E2=80=99s experience on the platf=
orm.

Musk=E2=80=99s claim is that Twitter counts spam bots in its mDAU numbers. =
Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint says, no, obviously Twitter doesn=E2=80=99t do th=
at =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s just a thing that Musk made up to get out =
of the deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the spam bots=C2=A0exist=C2=A0and are annoyi=
ng. Twitter does a good job of excluding them from its count of monetizable=
 users, he says, but not of getting rid of them entirely. That=E2=80=99s no=
t fraud; it=E2=80=99s just a thing that annoys Zatko (and Musk).=C2=A0
The rest of the complaint is mostly like that too. The gist of it is that, =
when he worked there, Zatko felt like Twitter was disorganized and incompet=
ent, and because Twitter is a really important platform with lots of users,=
 that=E2=80=99s bad. =E2=80=9CMudge Discovers Egregious Deficiencies, Negli=
gence, Willful Ignorance, and Threats to National Security & Democracy=E2=
=80=9D is one representative section header. Basically =E2=80=9CTwitter was=
 bad at running a website.=E2=80=9D Which I think a lot of people already b=
elieved?
But if you believe Zatko=E2=80=99s claims, you could spin some legal argume=
nts from them. (Ann Lipton has  a good Twitter thread analyzing what Zatko=
=E2=80=99s claims could mean for Musk.) If Twitter was bad at safeguarding =
user data, did that violate the law (including in particular its  2011 sett=
lement with the Federal Trade Commission over user data)? Were Twitter=E2=
=80=99s securities filings misleading, because they didn=E2=80=99t disclose=
 all of its security vulnerabilities? When all this stuff comes out, will t=
hat cause a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D on Twitter=E2=80=99s =
business, which will let Musk get out of the deal? Meh, I don=E2=80=99t kno=
w.=C2=A0
Even if=C2=A0these claims are true, and even if they are evidence of fraud =
or=C2=A0material adverse effect, they are=C2=A0not evidence of anything tha=
t Musk=C2=A0has been complaining about. Musk would have to, like, send Twit=
ter a new termination letter saying =E2=80=9Cnever mind about the bot stuff=
,=C2=A0now I=E2=80=99m terminating the deal because of the security vulnera=
bility stuff.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But he could do that, why not. He=E2=80=99s not=
 limited to the excuses he=E2=80=99s already tried; if people keep finding =
him new excuses to get out of the deal, he can try those too. Maybe one wil=
l work.

